======== SAMPLE 1 ========
.

O fawn!

QUEEN:
The queen!

AURORA:
Nay, no, my friend, no, no no, no, no, she's a widow,
for she lived and died with her daughter.
Now, then, I see, what my heart is so short of
to save her; what my heart is so short of, wherefore
that I can do it; what my heart is so short of,
that it cannot move more than a twister to an oak.
Then, my son, I tell thee, let thy son
be a widow.

QUEEN:
Hark!

AURORA:
Ay, the boy's not a widow: I am a widow,
for my son is a widow; for his widow,
if I hear it, I do not think he is.

QUEEN:
Then, you know our boy is like my daughter!

AURORA:
True, my true daughter.

QUEEN:
Go; and see her; or else, you'll be found
in a bed with her.

AURORA:
Come on, tell me where she was.

QUEEN:
The queen!

AURORA:
Where is she? what now? what now?

QUEEN:
O, here she's in a chamber, for all the ladies to go
and see her.

AURORA:
Ay, O, this is a chamber that women should play,
where there are so many of them, but I could play,
I could weep at it; not a poor woman, but
a poor queen, but a poor queen.

QUEEN:
What then is she!

AURORA:
She is too proud and too fair and too rich!

QUEEN:
Why, my boy!

AURORA:
That is a great man, for that is a true man!

QUEEN:
Why, the proud and fair man; not that's a true man,
no, but, if thou wilt take away one of his
poles, thou shall get no further: that is a false
man.

QUEEN:
Why, then thou shalt be a true man.

AURORA:
No: this is a housewife of poor
name, my child; to whom thou shouldst be all thyself
whom that thy children should be the rest of their young
and their downdings, for that matter, if thou
havest, if thou's not bound to thee, in any
way bound to thee as well as thou shalt.

QUEEN:
What, no, no! this is a housewife!

AURORA:
That man comes here as a widow.

QUEEN:
Hark! how she made us mad?

AURORA:
Well, she made us mad as they met to go to sleep;
and as she put herself in their company
there was this unbalanced woman in the house,
she said, as she should be, that she should go
to sleep in a man's house and that she should
beat up this fool and say 'no, my boy.'

QUEEN:
Madam, you'll be heard, what I was hearing to
this man, was that this man had a wife and
wife and two children; no woman but
that wife and two children; what dost thou
think thou mayst hear?

AURORA:
That it hath been my father's business to marry
his daughters to give him the throne; thou
shouldst take such an odd oath that thou,
thither with all your hearts, and all thy bodies,
would die this way to marry.

QUEEN:
How, that thou dost have done with thyself!

Horny, sad fellow! he had been my father.

AURORA:
Well, my shame, my shame, he was with him;
for in vain have you and the rest of the
family of London drunk of your sorrows;
'lose my blood, make my cheeks pale, my lips pale,
and my nails pale in proportion with my age;
not even the blood of a man!

QUEEN:
So, madam, I think thou must weep all over again;
to be revenged upon thee.

AURORA:
It is not for the worse that I did curse my child,
as thou hast done with me.
